DESIGNING THE COVERS
How will you know where the boundary is between the front cover and the back
cover? We'll create a divider between the two sides and center it on your canvas.
Select the pen tool from the toolbox on the left.
Click above your canvas vertically and in the center
horizontally and hold down the CTRL key on your
keyboard. As you hold CTRL you'll notice it snaps the red
line that appears. Move your mouse to below the canvas,
centered vertically, in a straight line from the first click
you made. (Click from left to right on the canvas if your
card is horizontal!)
CLICK 1
CLICK 2

canvas. Inkscape can take care of that for us. In the Inkscape menu, select Object >
Align and Distribute... - this will take care of the centering for us. Click on the

CREATING YOUR DESIGN!
If you're designing a card or journal, you might want
to start out using the text tool. Write 'My Journal'
on the front if it's a journal, and think of a nice
phrase if it's a card, such as 'Happy Holidays!' or
'Season's Greetings!'
There is a lot of nice clipart available right from
Inkscape that you can use in your design. Go to File >
Import from Open Clip Art Library in the Inkscape
menu, and search for clip art. When you click on the
Open button, the artwork will be placed into your
canvas. It will be bitmap, though. If you want to be
able to change the artwork, visit
http://openclipart.org in your web browser and
download the SVG from there.
An example cover design.

DESIGNING THE CARD INSIDE
So now you've designed the front cover (and a back cover, if you want.) It's time to
design the inside of your card or journal. We're going to create a new file for this.
SAVING THE COVERs IN SVG & PDF
Here's how to save your cover design as an SVG (so you can change it later) and as a
PDF (so you can print and share it.)
First, save your clipart by going to Extensions > Images > Embed Images. Click
the Apply button and wait for it to finish, then close the window.
Next, save your SVG by going to File > Save As... Name your file (I'm calling mine
GreetingCardCover.svg) and make sure the file ends in .svg! Choose a location to
save it on the left side of the dialog (I picked the 'My Files' folder) and click on
the 'Save' button on the lower right.
Finally, save your card covers as a PDF by selecting File > Print... from the menu
and choosing the 'Print to File' printer. Under the Name field type something like
GreetingCardCover.pdf; under Save in Folder choose 'My Files'; make sure
Output Format has PDF selected. Finally, press the Print button in the lower right.
CREATING A NEW FILE FOR THE COVERS
You're going to want to follow the same steps you followed in 'Setting up your canvas'
on the front of this booklet. The difference is in what each side of the canvas means.
Check out the diagrams below to understand where to place things on the canvas.
